lead_paragraph: It was 1985. I was 12 and standing next to my mother in a police station in Greenwich Village. She was a pretty red-haired gal in her late 30s, but the three police officers she was talking to weren’t looking at her. They were looking at the bag of crack vials she had in her hands, confused about what they were. I wasn’t confused. We had a lot of crack vials in our apartment at that point. Hundreds of them. My brothers and I played with them in Washington Square Park. We carried them around in our pockets the way other kids carried marbles.

abstract: Lives column by Beth
snippet: Lives column by Beth
lead_paragraph: 'I don't run across many people who have kind things to say about their exes. It's rare. But Doug was exceptional. The Saturday before the World Trade Center disaster, he called to find out if I could pick him up Tuesday night. He lived in New Hampshire. We, our son, Zach, and I, live in Fountain Valley near Los Angeles. Doug was scheduled to come help us get Zach moved into his dorm at U.C.L.A. On Sept. 11, I was in Texas on business. We were driving to work when I heard the horrendous news. I immediately flashed: he was going to be flying in that morning. When I talked to my son, I said, 'Zach, your dad,' and he said, 'Yes, I know.' We confirmed he was on the flight. The financial officer of my company rented a car, and we drove back 22 hours.

abstract: Whether to share a place with his parents.
snippet: Whether to share a place with his parents.
lead_paragraph: There is a trend, the Internet tells me, of grown adults, sometimes even married and with kids of their own, moving back in with their parents. As much as I try to steer clear of trends, I have recently been considering this possibility, but in reverse. I grew up outside Miami, and when my youngest brother and I first moved to Brooklyn, my parents used to visit pretty often. When I married, the visits fell off. I think they were happy that I was taken care of: good job, good wife, good riddance. When I had kids, the visits started to pick up again. I didn’t take it personally. They are now those kinds of parents, meaning that they are now grandparents. Last year my parents rented for a few months in the neighborhood. Then about a month ago, on the phone, my mother told me that they were thinking of coming to Brooklyn.

She had supported Hillary Rodham Clinton in the primaries, and had resented a seemingly widespread assumption that, because she is black, she would back Barack Obama. But she ultimately did vote for him in the general election, and she now wanted to hear from him something, anything demonstrating that he grasped what things were like for people in her position: college-educated and urbane, with professional experience, fluency in several languages and no job prospects in sight.

lead_paragraph: When my best friend and I go to our favorite cafe in the Cihangir neighborhood near Taksim Square, in Istanbul, I usually get tavsan kanı. Known as ‘‘rabbit’s blood,’’ it’s just watered-down Turkish tea, served in a small tulip glass. I quit coffee and cigarettes a year ago, and generally I don’t feel the need for them anymore. But then one beautiful day this summer, we came across a certain family of beggars in the square.

abstract: He told me that he could not live without me, and that he would not stop telling me how he felt. And then he disappeared.
snippet: He told me that he could not live without me, and that he would not stop telling me how he felt. And then he disappeared.
lead_paragraph: DREAM was my student. The handle on his e-mail account: dream come true. All of my students in Thailand had nicknames. It’s customary, Thai names being so long. The English nicknames are a more recent development. In my year working at a university there, I taught English to Pond, Gold, Baseball (sister of Basketball), Year, Earth, Cake, Talk, Dear, Boy, Gift, King, Bird and Birth.

abstract: Sometimes you just need a fake antique from the Beijing flea market.
snippet: Sometimes you just need a fake antique from the Beijing flea market.
lead_paragraph: Autumn in Beijing, where we had gone to live, and my husband and I were surrounded by Chinese “antiques” at the biggest flea market in town — detritus of a country embracing free-market enterprise. There were rows of vintage Mao wristwatches, red and black feng-shui meters, brightly embroidered Tibetan booties and slim, early-Communist-era cigarette cases. We could buy tea-stained calligraphy scrolls and vintage Cultural Revolution posters. We could bargain over the earliest Chinese radios and glass mirrors with etchings of the Imperial family. We could bargain over just about anything.

snippet: New York Times Neediest Cases Fund appeal; many former New Yorkers are preserving their link to city by contributing to fund (M)
lead_paragraph: Scattered by time and circumstance to new hometowns across the nation, many former New Yorkers preserve a link to the great glittering metropolis by contributing to The New York Times Neediest Cases Fund. Their donations -- with postmarks from Wisconsin to Texas, California to Massachusetts -- reach their former neighbors in the five boroughs who are poor and need help.
